<ArticleLayout
  title="Mattress Sizes Australia: Room, Base and Current Mattress Guide"
  seoTitle="Mattress Sizes Australia: Dimensions and Current Models"
  description="Compare Australian mattress sizes, room and base checks, trial conditions and current mattress examples reviewed for availability in July 2026."
  category="Bedroom"
  date="Published July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-23"
  readingTime="12 minute read"
  faqs={faqs}
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/guides/mattress-sizes-australia.webp"
  imageAlt="A queen mattress being measured on a black metal bed in a colourful bedroom with cobalt bedding and an aubergine wall"
>
  <p>
    A larger mattress changes more than the sleeping surface. It changes the bed frame footprint,
    the space beside the bed, the cost of sheets and protectors, and whether the mattress can turn
    through the hallway. Mattress height can also make an existing bedside table or fitted sheet
    unsuitable.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start with the room and base, then compare comfort and construction. Australian Home Collective
    has not slept on or tested the current models in this guide. They are examples with current
    manufacturer information and useful independent evidence, not a promise of comfort for every
    person.
  </p>

  <h2>Common Australian mattress sizes</h2>
  <p>
    The figures below are common nominal dimensions. A single or double may be listed one or two
    centimetres differently, and imported frames can follow another market. Use the exact product
    sheet before buying a mattress, base, protector or fitted sheet.
  </p>
  <p class="table-hint">Swipe sideways to compare the full table.</p>
  <div class="comparison-wrap">
    <table class="comparison-table">
      <caption>Common nominal mattress dimensions in Australia</caption>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col">Size</th>
          <th scope="col">Common mattress dimensions</th>
          <th scope="col">Length difference</th>
          <th scope="col">Planning point</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Single</td>
          <td>92 W × 188 L cm</td>
          <td>Shorter length</td>
          <td>Check bunks, trundles and older frames carefully.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Long single</td>
          <td>92 W × 203 L cm</td>
          <td>15 cm longer than a common single</td>
          <td>Useful for a tall solo sleeper or some adjustable bases.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>King single</td>
          <td>107 W × 203 L cm</td>
          <td>15 cm longer than a common single</td>
          <td>More width for one person, but not offered in every range.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Double</td>
          <td>138 W × 188 L cm</td>
          <td>Shorter length</td>
          <td>Compact for two people and may feel short for a taller sleeper.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Queen</td>
          <td>153 W × 203 L cm</td>
          <td>Longer length</td>
          <td>Common choice with broad availability of frames and bedding.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>King</td>
          <td>183 W × 203 L cm</td>
          <td>Same common length as queen</td>
          <td>Add the full frame width before judging room clearance.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Super king</td>
          <td>203 W × 203 L cm</td>
          <td>Square sleeping surface</td>
          <td>Limited ranges and a much larger frame, linen and delivery task.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Measure the bed frame, not only the mattress</h2>
  <p>
    A queen mattress may be 153 cm wide, while a frame with rails, upholstery or a broad bedhead is
    wider and longer. Record the maximum outside dimensions. Mark that rectangle on the floor and
    include the depth of any leaning bedhead or drawers that extend from the sides.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open the bedroom door, wardrobe and bedside drawers. Walk the route used at night and when making
    the bed. If the room needs a cot, mobility aid, laundry basket or access from both sides, include
    it in the test rather than treating empty floor as spare space.
  </p>

  <h2>Current mattresses checked in July 2026</h2>
  <p>
    These Australian online models were available when checked on 23 July 2026 and had current
    independent test or reliability evidence. They represent different approaches to adjustable
    firmness and hybrid construction. Comfort remains personal, and a strong brand result does not
    mean every body or sleeping position will suit the same model.
  </p>
  <p class="table-hint">Swipe sideways to compare the full table.</p>
  <div class="comparison-wrap">
    <table class="comparison-table">
      <caption>Current Australian mattress examples</caption>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col">Model</th>
          <th scope="col">Published construction</th>
          <th scope="col">Evidence checked</th>
          <th scope="col">Main ownership question</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Sleeping Duck Mach II</td>
          <td>31 cm hybrid with replaceable firmness foam inside the mattress</td>
          <td>Tom's Guide Australia made it its top 2026 pick after long term use; Sleeping Duck also led satisfaction in a CHOICE owner survey</td>
          <td>Will adjustable firmness offset the weight and return conditions?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Koala Plus Mattress</td>
          <td>28 cm foam mattress with a reversible comfort layer and two firmness settings</td>
          <td>Current model with a large manufacturer owner review set; Koala ranked ahead of Ikea in a 2025 CHOICE brand comparison</td>
          <td>Do the two firmness choices and foam feel suit both sleepers?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Ecosa Pure Mattress</td>
          <td>29 cm hybrid with pocket springs, micro coils, latex and an adjustable comfort layer</td>
          <td>Tom's Guide included it in its tested 2026 Australian list; Ecosa led mattress in a box reliability in a 2025 CHOICE survey</td>
          <td>Will the firmer feel, heavy construction and material mix suit the household?</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Firmness labels are not a common measurement</h2>
  <p>
    Medium on one mattress may feel firmer than medium on another. Body weight, sleeping position,
    temperature and the base below the mattress all affect the experience. A number out of ten is a
    brand description, not a standard shared across the industry.
  </p>
  <p>
    Try the normal sleeping position for more than a few minutes where possible. For an online model,
    read the complete trial conditions before opening the package and keep the mattress protected as
    required. A trial is valuable only when the household can comply with its minimum period, pickup
    area and return process.
  </p>

  <h2>The base can change support and warranty eligibility</h2>
  <p>
    Check whether the manufacturer permits solid platforms, slats or adjustable bases. Slat width,
    gap, centre support and weight capacity can be specified. An old base that sags or has wide gaps
    may change how the mattress feels and may not meet warranty conditions.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the internal frame rather than relying on its size label. Check whether edge rails sit
    above the support surface and whether the mattress can expand without being pinched. A heavy
    hybrid also needs a frame and floor suited to its total loaded weight.
  </p>

  <h2>Mattress height changes the complete bed</h2>
  <p>
    Add mattress height to the top of the base. Sit on the resulting height and check whether both
    feet reach the floor comfortably. A 31 cm mattress on a tall ensemble may place the sleeping
    surface well above a low bedside table.
  </p>
  <p>
    Deep mattresses need fitted sheets and protectors with enough pocket depth. Allow extra fabric
    for toppers. Check that bedding will not pull tight at the corners or slip off when an adjustable
    base moves.
  </p>

  <h2>Delivery involves weight, turns and expansion space</h2>
  <p>
    A mattress delivered in a box still has weight and a large final size. Check the box dimensions,
    stair turns, lift limits and who will move it into position. Unroll it on the intended base if the
    instructions allow, because a fully expanded king mattress is much harder to turn in a small room.
  </p>
  <p>
    Read the opening window, expansion guidance and advice about sleeping on it. Keep children and
    pets clear while packaging releases. Arrange old mattress removal before delivery where the home
    cannot safely store both.
  </p>

  <h2>Look beyond comfort on the first night</h2>
  <p>
    CHOICE surveys show that owners report sinking, sagging, weight and body discomfort among common
    problems. Independent durability testing and longer owner experience provide different evidence
    from a short showroom trial. Use both where available.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Read how the warranty defines a measurable indentation.</li>
    <li>Check rotation and care instructions.</li>
    <li>Confirm whether the cover can be removed or only spot cleaned.</li>
    <li>Ask how firmness parts, covers and other components are replaced.</li>
    <li>Review low ratings for repeated problems, not isolated comfort preferences.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What stands out in the current examples</h2>
  <div class="advice-stack">
    <section>
      <h3>Sleeping Duck: the broadest adjustment system</h3>
      <p>
        The Mach II allows firmness foam to be changed after delivery and can provide different feels
        across each side in larger sizes. That flexibility earned strong independent attention and
        can reduce the risk when two sleepers disagree on firmness.
      </p>
      <p>
        It is 31 cm high and heavy. Read the 100 night guarantee in full, including the adjustment
        process and household return limits, before treating the trial as effortless.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Koala Plus: a simpler two feel design</h3>
      <p>
        The Koala Plus uses a reversible comfort layer to provide two firmness choices without the
        spring system of the other examples. It may suit someone who wants a foam mattress and a
        straightforward adjustment rather than many internal zones.
      </p>
      <p>
        Koala's trial terms vary by location and pickup coverage. Check current costs and requirements,
        and do not rely on a review that may refer to an earlier generation.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>Ecosa Pure: a layered hybrid with a firmer review signal</h3>
      <p>
        The Pure combines two spring systems with latex and foam. Tom's Guide found it supportive and
        breathable in its testing but firmer than its official description might suggest.
      </p>
      <p>
        Its weight and lack of end handles were practical review cautions. Check who will rotate or
        move it and whether the permitted base matches the one already in the room.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <h2>A practical buying checklist</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Confirm the exact mattress width, length and height.</li>
    <li>Mark the complete bed frame footprint on the floor.</li>
    <li>Open doors and drawers and walk the normal routes.</li>
    <li>Check the base type, slat gaps, support and weight capacity.</li>
    <li>Measure the delivery box and every turn to the bedroom.</li>
    <li>Read the complete trial, return and pickup terms.</li>
    <li>Check sheet and protector pocket depth.</li>
    <li>Review durability evidence and warranty indentation terms.</li>
  </ul>

